{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:06:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:06:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15770"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15770"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.27,0.09,0.37,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3833"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the surgical outpatient clinic with his son regarding a skin lesion on his right lower leg. The lesion has been present for two months and occasionally bleeds onto his bedsheets. He has a medical history of hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, atrial fibrillation and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His regular medications include apixaban. He lives independently and manages his own activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1.5 cm skin lesion on the lateral aspect of his right anterior shin (Image). A biopsy reveals a well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. The plastic surgery consultant has recommended surgical excision.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following surgical margins is most appropriate for excision of this squamous cell carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["10 mm","20 mm","3 mm","4 mm","8 mm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) that is less than 2 cm in diameter on the lower leg. The most appropriate surgical margin for excision in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003E4 mm\u003C/strong\u003E. This margin has been shown to provide complete excision in over 95% of well-differentiated SCCs of this size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E3 mm\u003C/strong\u003E margin would be inadequate and associated with a higher risk of incomplete excision and local recurrence. This margin might be considered for small, well-defined superficial SCCs in low-risk areas, but not for a leg lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E8 mm\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E10 mm\u003C/strong\u003E margins would be excessive for this well-differentiated tumour. These wider margins are typically reserved for high-risk SCCs with features such as poor differentiation, perineural invasion, or location in high-risk sites like the ear or lip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E20 mm\u003C/strong\u003E margin would be inappropriate and unnecessarily morbid for this lesion. Such wide margins are typically reserved for melanoma or other aggressive skin malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe choice of surgical margin depends on several factors including tumour size, differentiation, location, and presence of high-risk features. For standard SCCs less than 2 cm in diameter without high-risk features, a 4 mm margin provides the optimal balance between ensuring complete excision and minimising the surgical defect. The lower leg location in this case does not constitute a high-risk site that would necessitate wider margins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Well-differentiated squamous cell carcinomas less than 2cm in diameter require a minimum 4mm surgical margin for complete excision.","Wider margins (6-10mm) are required for high-risk features including poor differentiation, perineural invasion, or location on high-risk sites.","Clinical margin assessment should be performed under good lighting with magnification to identify subtle tumour extension."],"references":["Nabhas AF, Scarbrough CA, Trotter S. A review of the global guidelines on surgical margins for nonmelanoma skin cancers. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol. 2017;10(4):37-46."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15770"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21183"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21183"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4rw0Xe3IHhNhYN9N8EGWhvQDqvikbs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4rw0Xe3IHhNhYN9N8EGWhvQDqvikbs.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":478}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T22:49:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T22:50:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type